    "# AVN Getting Started Tutorial"
   ]
  },

   "source": [
    "import avn.dataloading\n",
    "import avn.segmentation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "68b6cd3e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Simple Segmentation"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "3836ba6e",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In this section of the tutorial, I will be segmenting 50 song files from a single bird using MFCC derivative threshold segmentation. First, let's specify the path to the folder containing the song files:\n"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 2,
   "id": "cfccda2d",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "Bird_ID = \"G402\"\n",
    "song_folder = \"../sample_data/\" + Bird_ID + \"/\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "4e8dfef4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now, we will instantiate an MFCCDerivative class object, which we will then use for segmentation. Segmentation using other criteria will differ in terms of which segmenter is used. Currently the options available are RMSE, RMSEDerivative, MFCC and MFCCDerivative. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 3,
   "id": "833fab21",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "segmenter = avn.segmentation.MFCCDerivative()"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "1165f4e4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Now that we've created the segmenter, we can use it to segment the songs in `song_folder`. We must also specify the value of the upper and lower segmentation thresholds. "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 4,
   "id": "85fb6f3b",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "seg_data = segmenter.make_segmentation_table(Bird_ID, song_folder, \n",
    "                                            upper_threshold = 0.10, \n",
    "                                            lower_threshold = -0.1)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "98120706",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "`seg_data` is an instance of the avn.segmentation.SegData class. It's `.seg_table` attribute contains a dataframe with the onset and offset times of every syllable, generated by `segmenter`:"
   ]
  },

   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "36fd49b4",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "These syllable onset and offset timestamps can be used to extract individual syllables from files for further analyses, like syllable labeling or calculating acoustic features. To save this table locally for future use you can use the following function: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 6,
   "id": "2e4ccdd5",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [],
   "source": [
    "out_file_dir = \"../sample_data/\"\n",
    "seg_data.save_as_csv(out_file_dir)"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "2e229213",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This will create a file called `[Bird_ID]_seg_table.csv`. In our case, that is \"G402_seg_table.csv\""
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "78ac4a15",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "## Threshold Optimization"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "8ae4a198",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "In the example above, we used an upper_threshold value of 0.1. This threshold generally works well for all zebra finch song, in my experience, but you may want to test other thresholds to see how they compare. \n",
    "\n",
    "One way to test different thresholds is to use the avn.segmentation.Plot functions to visualize syllable boundaries over a spectrogram of the song:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 7,
   "id": "c6c4622c",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "avn.segmentation.Plot.plot_segmentations(seg_data, seg_label = \"Upper threshold = 0.1, Onsets\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "75baca05",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "The white lines in the spectrogram above represent the syllable onset times. Lets see what they would look like if we used a lower upper segmentation threshold: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 8,
   "id": "034141a3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "seg_data_001 = segmenter.make_segmentation_table(Bird_ID, song_folder,\n",
    "                                                upper_threshold = 0.01, \n",
    "                                                lower_threshold = -0.01)\n",
    "\n",
    "avn.segmentation.Plot.plot_segmentations(seg_data_001, seg_label = \"Upper threshold = 0.01, Onsets\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "6be57b7a",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "It is pretty clear that the segmentation threshold here was too low becuase there are many false positive syllable onset detections. What if we use a much higher upper segmentation threshold:"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 9,
   "id": "ea285b25",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 1 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "seg_data_02 = segmenter.make_segmentation_table(Bird_ID, song_folder, \n",
    "                                               upper_threshold = 0.2, \n",
    "                                               lower_threshold = -0.01)\n",
    "avn.segmentation.Plot.plot_segmentations(seg_data_02, seg_label = \"Upper threshold = 0.2, Onsets\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "f77918c0",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "This shows that an upper threshold of 0.2 is much too high, because we miss many syllable onsets. \n",
    "\n",
    "Testing many different thresholds in this way can be very tedious. Another option available in avn is to plot the segmentation criteria (in this case the MFCC derivative) over the spectrogram. Looking at the segmentation criteria values can help inform what a reasonable threshold would be: "
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "code",
   "execution_count": 12,
   "id": "8d6ee4e3",
   "metadata": {},
   "outputs": [
    {
     "data": {
      "image/png": "\n",
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 2 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {
      "needs_background": "light"
     },
     "output_type": "display_data"
    },
    {
     "data": {
      "text/plain": [
       "<Figure size 1440x360 with 0 Axes>"
      ]
     },
     "metadata": {},
     "output_type": "display_data"
    }
   ],
   "source": [
    "avn.segmentation.Plot.plot_seg_criteria(seg_data, segmenter, \"MFCC Derivative\")"
   ]
  },
  {
   "cell_type": "markdown",
   "id": "41f4da79",
   "metadata": {},
   "source": [
    "Looking at the MFCC Derivative trace and the right y-axis, we can see why 0.1 is a good threshold. It is high enough that only true syllable onsets will cross, but low enough that we don't miss any syllables. \n",
    "\n",
    "Using this method to find a good segmentation threshold can still be quite tedious, however. "
   ]
